In the following sections, you can find details about the reports and inquiries that provide information about items with lot and serial numbers. ==Viewing the Location of Items with Lot and Serial Numbers== By using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_70_00|Inventory Lot/Serial History] ([~/?ScreenId=IN407000|IN407000]) form, you can find the physical location of an item by the lot or serial number assigned to it.{br}
You can use the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_30_00|Lot/Serial Numbers] ([~/?ScreenId=IN613000|IN613000]) report to view the list of items, along with their lot and serial numbers, that are located at the selected warehouse, location, or both. ==Viewing the Item Quantities== When you want to view the documents that include the item you specify and that are in process in the system (not completed yet), you can use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form. You can also use this form to view the quantities of items in a particular warehouse or location (or both).{br}
When you want to view the on-hand quantities of particular items and the total cost of inventory by inventory account, with details for different warehouses, you can use the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_55_00|Inventory Valuation] ([~/?ScreenId=IN615500|IN615500]) report.

If your organization sells or purchases items with multiple attributes (such as T-shirts that have different materials, sizes, colors, and brands), you may want to generate items with various attributes automatically by using predefined templates. To do this, you can use the matrix items functionality in Acumatica ERP. A matrix item is a stock or non-stock item that corresponds to a physical product or a service with particular set of attributes. You define related matrix items in the system by using a template item, which provides the default settings for the particular group of matrix items.{br}

The functionality of matrix items is available if the ''Matrix Items'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form.{br}{TOC}
==Learning Objectives==
In this chapter, you will learn how to do the following:[anchor|#ul_dmx_2lv_pr]
*Configure item classes to be used for matrix items
*Create template items for matrix items
*Create matrix items based on template items
*Process purchase orders that contain matrix items
*Process sales orders that contain matrix items

==Applicable Scenarios==
You may need to create matrix items in the following cases:[anchor|#_7165d0ed-fbf9-4bca-b563-a0155c7a9310]
*Your organization purchases items or services with multiple variants
*Your organization sells items or services with multiple variants
*Your organization sells items online

==Template Items==
Template items are high-level items that contain default settings for matrix items. Each template item exists solely to provide default settings for a group of matrix items; template items cannot be added to inventory transactions or to AP, AR, sales, or purchase documents. You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_30_00|Template Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN203000|IN203000]) form to create, modify, and delete template items.{br}

Template items are based on item classes, which are created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form. When you create a template item, you specify an item class that provides the default settings for the template item. The item class must contain attributes that have the ''Variant'' attribute category and the ''Combo'' control type; you will use these variables to generate matrix items based on the template item. Before you create an item class, you must createthe specific attributes to be used for matrix items on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_50_00|Attributes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS205000|CS205000]) form, if they don’t already exist.{br}

For each template item, you specify the following settings in addition to the settings inherited from the item class:[anchor|#_1d9174b3-6ab9-4750-bf9f-2ca5ec317ddc]
*The default attributes that are used in the rows and columns of a matrix. As these attributes, you can select the attributes that provide values for variants of items (such as size and color for T-shirts). For other attributes with the ''Variant'' category (if there are any), you select the particular value when creating matrix items. In the example with T-shirts, you can create the group of matrix items for T-shirts made of a particular material (such as cotton) and select particular sizes and colors as item variants in matrix cells.
*The settings of the identifiers of the matrix items generated by using the template item. The identifiers of matrix items can be segmented and are generated automatically. In the segments, you can use attribute values and captions, the template ID and description, constants, automatically generated numbers, and spaces.
*The settings to be used for the descriptions for matrix items. Descriptions are generated automatically when you create matrix items. These descriptions can be segmented, and the segments can be based on the same entities as the segments of item identifiers.

You can specify the prices and discounts for a template item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_00|Sales Prices] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202000|AR202000]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_10|Sales Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202010|AR202010]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_95_00|Discounts] ([~/?ScreenId=AR209500|AR209500]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_20_20_00|Vendor Prices] ([~/?ScreenId=AP202000|AP202000]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_20_20_10|Vendor Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AP202010|AP202010]), and [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_20_50_00|Vendor Discounts] ([~/?ScreenId=AP205000|AP205000]) forms. These prices and discounts will be applied to the matrix items related to this template item if specific prices and discounts are not specified for the individual matrix items of the template item.
==Matrix Items==
When a template item is created and its settings have been specified, you create matrix items either on the '''Create Matrix Items''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_30_00|Template Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN203000|IN203000]) form or on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_35_00|Create Matrix Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN203500|IN203500]) form. It is not necessary to create matrix items with all possible combinations of attributes at once. You can create only the set of items that is currently required and then create other items later as they are needed. Then on the '''Matrix Items''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_30_00|Template Items] form, you can view the list of items created based on the selected template item.{br}

To check if a particular item is a matrix item, you can open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form and view the value of the '''Template ID''' box on the '''General Settings''' tab. If the box is empty, the item is not a matrix item. If the ID of a template item is specified in this box, the item is a matrix item.{br}

The settings of an individual matrix item can be changed by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form (depending on whether the item is a stock or non-stock item). If you need to change a particular setting for all matrix items of a template item, you can make these changes in the template item settings on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_30_00|Template Items] form and then apply these changes to all related matrix items by clicking the '''Apply to Matrix Items''' button on the form toolbar.((({S:Warn}When you click the '''Apply to Matrix Items''' button, all specific settings of matrix items will be overwritten with the template item settings.
)))
If you need to completely remove a particular matrix item from the system, you can do this on the '''Matrix Items''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_30_00|Template Items] form. You can also remove the item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form (depending on whether the item is a stock or non-stock item) by clicking '''Delete''' on the form toolbar.
==Document Processing with Matrix Items==
You can add multiple matrix items to purchase orders on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) form and to sales orders on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form by clicking the '''Add Matrix Item''' button on the table toolbar of the '''Document Details''' tab.{br}

In the '''Add Matrix Item''' dialog box, which opens, you can use either a table view or a matrix view for adding matrix items to the documents. In the table view, you select a template item and specify the attribute values of the matrix items that you need to add to the document. In this view, you can select any set of available attribute values, even if a matrix item with this set does not exist in the system; for a new item, in the table of the '''Add Matrix Item: Table View''' dialog box, the '''New''' check box is selected. The system generates the new items on the fly when you close the dialog box and add the items to the document.{br}

In the matrix view, which is opened when you click the '''Open Matrix View''' button in the '''Add Matrix Item: Table View''' dialog box, you can select existing matrix items by entering the required quantities in the matrix.[anchor|#_d6338c5d-ddd7-42bf-8160-e8c6f6ca96f8]((({S:Danger}You must use either the table view or matrix view to select the matrix items to be added to the document. If you select the items in the table view and then switch to the matrix view, the selection of items in the table view will be discarded.
)))

In the following sections, you can find details about the reports and inquiry forms you may want to review to gather information about matrix items. [anchor|#_a731b38a-aa04-4959-9c49-e00f077c4cc7]((({S:Warn}If you do not see a particular report or form that is described, you may have signed in to the system with a user account that does not have access rights to the report or form. Contact your system administrator to obtain access to any needed reports or forms.
))){br}{TOC}
==Viewing Availability Details for Matrix Items==
You can view availability information about the matrix items that have been generated by using a particular template item and stored in a particular warehouse by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_15_00|Matrix Inventory Summary] ([~/?ScreenId=IN401500|IN401500]) form.
==Printing Documents that Contain Matrix Items==
To prepare a printable form of a purchase order that contains matrix items, you use the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\PO_64_10_10|Matrix Purchase Order] ([~/?ScreenId=PO641010|PO641010]) report.{br}

To prepare a printable form of a sales order that contains matrix items, you use the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\SO_64_10_20|Matrix Sales Order] ([~/?ScreenId=SO641020|SO641020]) report.{br}

To prepare a printable form of a invoice or memo that contains matrix items, you use the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\SO_64_30_10|Matrix Invoice/Memo] ([~/?ScreenId=SO643010|SO643010]) report.

An organization can have multiple warehouses in Acumatica ERP, and different groups of employees may work with these warehouses in the system. To limit in the system the set of employees who work with a particular warehouse, you can create restriction groups to display the warehouse for only employees who are responsible for tasks that involve this warehouse. If the employees who work with the same warehouse perform only specific tasks (such as accepting goods and creating purchase orders), you can provide these employees with access to only the forms that they should use.{br}
In this topic, you can find information about configuring the security of warehouses in Acumatica ERP.[anchor|#_98e853b8-e0b4-440b-8a19-485472ea8b0f]((({S:Warn}In Acumatica ERP, you can configure groups with direct and inverse restriction. In this topic, for simplicity, groups with direct restriction are used in examples. You can use inverse restriction groups in the same way as you use direct restriction groups. For details on the types of restriction groups, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Types_of_Restriction_Groups|Types of Restriction Groups]. ))){br}{TOC} ==Usage Scenarios== The most common scenarios of managing the security of warehouses are the following:[anchor|#_5f60ca2b-471f-457a-bd64-b28264e40516] *Managing access to forms based on employees&rsquo; functional roles: If employees perform specific tasks (such as receiving goods and creating purchase orders), you can provide the employees access to the forms they use in their work, and revoke access for forms that they shouldn&rsquo;t use. For details, see [[#_7ee4b6ba-c3a5-46d9-a4f7-bd85fda637b4|Access to Forms Based on Roles]. *Managing the visibility of particular warehouses by user: If you have created multiple warehouses in Acumatica ERP, you can restrict the visibility of warehouses to users on forms by using restriction groups. For details, see [[#_83e9713d-f736-4c02-ae67-3ce78bf3c078|Visibility of Warehouses by User]. *:((({S:Warn}You can create and manage multiple warehouses in Acumatica ERP only if the ''Multiple Warehouses'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. )))
In addition to managing the visibility of warehouses in whole, you can restrict the visibility of particular inventory items. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\RS__con_Restriction_Groups_for_Subitems|Inventory Item Security].[anchor|#_7ee4b6ba-c3a5-46d9-a4f7-bd85fda637b4] ==Access to Forms Based on Roles== By using the forms of the User Security submodule, you can use user roles in Acumatica ERP to give employees access to forms related to working with warehouses. A role can correspond to an area of responsibility for an employee who performs warehouse-related tasks, such as creating purchase orders, accepting goods, and preparing replenishment. If needed, you can assign multiple roles to an employee. For more information about user roles, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access].{br}
Consider the following examples of roles for employees who work with inventory and order management:[anchor|#_c5004388-84a3-44b7-9dd2-dc3f08893db0] *''Supervisor'': A role for an employee who configures the Inventory submodule and manages work with the submodule. This role should have access to the forms related to inventory processes, such as the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. *''Data Entry Clerk'': A role for an employee who creates documents on data entry forms. You should provide access to such forms as [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_20_00|Issues] ([~/?ScreenId=IN302000|IN302000]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_10_00|Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=IN301000|IN301000]), or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_40_00|Transfers] ([~/?ScreenId=IN304000|IN304000]). *''Purchasing Manager'': A role for an employee who is responsible for replenishment. For this role, you should provide access to the '''Replenishment''' node of the '''Processes''' tab of the Inventory module. [anchor|#_83e9713d-f736-4c02-ae67-3ce78bf3c078] ==Visibility of Warehouses by User== By default, all employees who have access to forms of the inventory and order management modules can see all warehouses created in the system. By using the forms of the Row-Level Security module, you can configure the system so that each warehouse is displayed only to users who work with this warehouse. You can use restriction groups to set up the visibility of warehouses to employees. For details on restriction groups, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Overview_of_Restriction_Groups|Restriction Groups in Acumatica ERP].{br}
For example, suppose that your system has the ''Wholesale'' and ''Retail'' warehouses defined, and you need to configure the visibility of these warehouses to users as follows:[anchor|#_db2bdfbf-29ba-46db-b8ad-90113c4268fe] *User S is a supervisor who should configure and manage both warehouses. *User C1 is a clerk who enters documents for the ''Wholesale'' warehouse. *User C2 is a clerk who enters documents for the ''Retail'' warehouse.
To configure the visibility of warehouses according to this example, you do the following on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_00|Warehouse Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102000|IN102000]) form:[anchor|#_14ead945-ff7d-46b6-b448-96b3a4aea0a6] #You create two restriction groups of type ''A'' (with direct restriction): ''Group 1'' for the ''Wholesale'' warehouse, and ''Group 2'' for the ''Retail'' warehouse. #In Group 1, you include User S, User C1, and the ''Wholesale'' warehouse. #In Group 2, you include User S, User C2, and the ''Retail'' warehouse.
The resulting visibility of warehouses will be the following:[anchor|#_cda8b83f-bba1-4a88-98dc-1c0bbf3d916f] *User S can see both the ''Wholesale'' and ''Retail'' warehouses. *User C1 can see only the ''Wholesale'' warehouse. *User C2 can see only the ''Retail'' warehouse. [anchor|#_2c2c87ec-204a-428c-86f4-85545b147219] ==Forms for Warehouse Security== In the following table, you can find the list of forms that you can use to manage restriction groups with warehouses and tasks that you can solve by using each form.[anchor|#_9cd3c9c9-eaab-437f-a3d5-d867f96e99cf] ===Forms for Warehouse Security=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="50%" ! Tasks !width="50%" ! Forms |- | To initially configure the visibility of a warehouse to users | [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_00|Warehouse Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102000|IN102000]) |- | To change the visibility of a warehouse in multiple restriction groups | [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_10|Restriction Groups by Warehouse] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102010|IN102010]) |- | To change the visibility of warehouses to a user in multiple restriction groups | [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_35|Restriction Groups by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201035|SM201035]) |}[anchor|#_c2ae633a-4298-4c86-b8ce-920ee4905b7f] For information about how to add or remove objects from a restriction group, see [HelpRoot_Administration\RS__con_Operations_Restriction_Groups|Operations with Restriction Groups]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Overview_of_Restriction_Groups|Restriction Groups in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Types_of_Restriction_Groups|Types of Restriction Groups] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_35|Restriction Groups by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201035|SM201035]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_10|Restriction Groups by Warehouse] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102010|IN102010]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_00|Warehouse Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102000|IN102000])

If your organization sells not only individual inventory items but also bundles of stock or non-stock items to its customers, you can treat these bundles as single items referred to as ''inventory kits'' in Acumatica ERP.{br}
In this chapter, you will find information about kit types and the configuration and management of kits. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#_a06d44bb-4481-4cc2-a284-40d71010e11b] {| class="checklist invisiblechecklist" | width="100%" |- | [anchor|#_80954e07-d91f-4ed5-9dc6-6a4343369b51] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Accounting_for_Kits|Inventory Item Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Stock_Kits|Stock Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Non_Stock_Kits|Non-Stock Kits]
| [anchor|#_d9dbdceb-0db0-4715-b399-98b1a079a1c3] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Stock_Kit|To Create a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Add_Revision_to_Stock_Kit|To Add a Revision to a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Assemble_Stock_Kit|To Assemble a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Disassemble_Stock_Kit|To Disassemble a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Non_Stock_Kit|To Create a Non-Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Non_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Non-Stock Kit]
|}

A kit is a bundle of stock and non-stock items that increases the value of the kit components. In Acumatica ERP, you can use kits of inventory items if your organization sells multiple inventory items together and wants to track these items as a whole. For example, suppose that an organization sells cheese and wine and also offers nicely packed baskets with a bottle of wine and a set of cheese that pairs well with this wine. To track these baskets in inventory, the organization uses kits, which include a bottle of wine, several cheeses, and a basket as stock items, and the delivery service and packaging as non-stock items.((({S:Warn}To use the kit functionality, make sure the ''Kit Assembly'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. ))) In this topic, you will read about kit types and revisions of kit specifications.{br}{TOC} ==Kit Types== You can create stock and non-stock kits. The main difference between these kit types is that the system tracks stock kits in inventory and does not track non-stock kits. The table below compares stock and non-stock kits.[anchor|#table_yfs_ffm_qy] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- ! !Stock Kit !Non-Stock Kit |- | colspan="3" | '''Components''' |- | Stock components | Yes | Yes |- | Non-stock components | Yes | Yes |- | Kit specification revisions | Multiple | One |- | Issue of components of a stock kit | When a kit is assembled | When a kit is issued |- | Expense accrual for non-stock components | When a kit is assembled | Not applicable |- | Lot- or serial-numbered components | Serial-numbered components can be used only in serial-numbered kits | Yes, except for components with the ''When-Used'' assignment method or the ''User-Enterable'' issue method |- | colspan="3" | '''Kit units''' (single entities of a kit) |- | Production/disassembly transactions | Required | Not applicable |- | Inventory tracking | Yes, as a regular stock item; stock components do not exist in inventory after the kit is assembled | No; stock components are tracked individually |- | Inventory value | Value of the kit unit received to inventory upon production | Values of its stock components |- | Availability tracking | Yes | No |- | Receipt of a kit unit | On kit production transaction | Not applicable |- | Issue of a kit unit | Inventory issue of the kit unit | Inventory issue of stock component units |- | Lot/serial tracking of kit units | Applicable | Not applicable |- | Disassembly revision | The revision used for assembly of a serial-tracked kit, and any revision of a non-serial-tracked kit | Not applicable |- | Sales return options | A kit unit | A kit unit or any kit components |- | Sales return revision | Not applicable | The current revision of the kit |} For detailed information on kits, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Stock_Kits|Stock Kits] and [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Non_Stock_Kits|Non-Stock Kits]. ==Kit Specifications and Revisions== To represent kits in the system, you create specifications, which define the stock and non-stock items included in a kit, by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500]) form. Each specification has at least one ''revision'', which is automatically created when you create a specification. A revision is a version of the same kit, which has minor differences from the previous version. For example, suppose that your organization sells computers and offers a keyboard, a mouse, a leather case, and software installation service as a kit. If you change the vendor of leather cases, you can just change the inventory item for the case in the kit instead of creating a new kit.{br}
For stock kits, you can create multiple revisions of the same specification. When you assemble a stock kit, you can use only the latest revision. If you need to disassemble a stock kit, you select the revision that was used for kit assembly.{br}
For non-stock kits, only one revision is created when you create a specification by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] form. You cannot add multiple revisions, as for stock kits.{br}
For each stock or non-stock kit revision, you can allow users to add components to the kit during assembly by selecting the '''Allow Component Addition''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] form and to change the quantity of components in the kit by selecting the '''Allow Component Qty. Variance''' check box for each kit component. Suppose that you are including in a kit specification stock components with the '''Divisible Unit''' check box cleared for the base UOMs on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. When you type the quantity in the '''Component Qty.''' box on the '''Stock Components''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] form, the system validates the quantities of the components included in the kit, making sure they are integers. If they are not, an error message is displayed, and you cannot save the specification until you type an integer quantity. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Non_Stock_Kits|Non-Stock Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Stock_Kits|Stock Kits] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500])

A stock kit is a bundle of stock and non-stock components. You create each kit and add it to inventory by processing a production transaction. The kit production subtracts the stock components from inventory and adds the kit units to inventory instead. After you have assembled a kit, you can disassemble it back to its components. When a stock kit is sold, one line item appears in the transaction, and the on-hand quantity of the kit is reduced.{br}
In this topic, you will find details about the configuration, assembly, disassembly, and cost calculation of stock kits.{br}{TOC} ==Configuration of Stock Kits== You do the following to configure a stock kit:[anchor|#_63d4a36d-6746-432c-b903-67587431857f] #You create item classes for kits with similar settings by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\Item_Classes_Implem_Activity|Item Classes for Stock Items: Implementation Activity]. #You create as many kits as you need by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. To indicate that each item is a kit, you select the '''Is a Kit''' check box on the '''General Settings''' tab of this form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Stock_Kit|To Create a Stock Kit]. #You create a specification for each kit by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500]) form. In the specification, you select the items that will be included in the kit and specify the settings of each component. Any lot- and serial-tracked stock items can be added to the specification of a stock kit. For details on this step, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Stock Kit]. #You create and release a kit assembly document by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] ([~/?ScreenId=IN307000|IN307000]) form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Assemble_Stock_Kit|To Assemble a Stock Kit]. #You assign sales prices to kits as follows: #*If you sell a limited number of kits, you assign the default prices on a per-kit basis by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form. #*If you are selling more than ten kits, you assign multiple sales prices to kits by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_10|Sales Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202010|AR202010]) form.
A stock kit may require a serial or lot number and an expiration date to be assigned when the kit is produced or sold, depending on the item class settings. For details on lot and serial numbers, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\Lot_and_Serial_Numbers_GeneralInfo|Items with Lot and Serial Numbers: General Information].{br}
You can disassemble a stock kit at any time. You may want to do this, for example, when its expiration date has approached. ==Assembly and Disassembly of Stock Kits== You must assemble a stock kit by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] ([~/?ScreenId=IN307000|IN307000]) form before you add the kit to a sales order. The kit assembly document lists the components with their quantities and costs, as determined by the kit specification. Each time a stock kit is assembled and its kit assembly document is released, the on-hand quantities of the items used as components are automatically decreased, and the on-hand quantity of the kits is increased. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Assemble_Stock_Kit|To Assemble a Stock Kit].{br}
On assembly of stock kits, the standard costs of the kit&rsquo;s non-stock components are recorded to the Expense Accrual accounts specified by the '''Use Inventory/Accrual Account From''' setting of the posting class (on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form) of each of the non-stock components.{br}
If disassembly might be required for a stock kit (for example, because of an expiration date), it can be performed in accordance with the revision used to assemble the kit. You can create and release a disassembly document with the ''Disassembly'' operation selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] form. The quantity of components extracted from the kit is estimated using the disassembly coefficient specified for each stock component. However, the quantities of stock components and non-stock components are not validated in any way, and you can manually adjust the calculated quantities.{br}
For details about how to disassemble a stock kit, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Disassemble_Stock_Kit|To Disassemble a Stock Kit].{br}
On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] ([~/?ScreenId=IN307000|IN307000]) form, when you assemble or disassemble a kit for which the '''Divisible Unit''' check box is cleared for the base UOMs on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form, the system validates the quantity of the kit: It checks to be sure that the quantity is an integer and displays an error message if it is not.{br}
If a kit that you assemble or disassemble includes stock components for which the '''Divisible Unit''' check box is cleared for the base UOMs on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form, the system also validates the quantities of the stock components in the document. It makes sure that the quantities are integers and displays an error message if they are not. ==Cost Calculation For Stock Kits== The assembly of stock kits (with valuation methods other than the standard cost method) creates a new cost layer. The cost of a stock kit is calculated based on the costs of components when the document is released. The total cost of the kit is the total cost of stock components according to the specification&rsquo;s revision, the cost of components added during assembly, and the rates of non-stock components of the ''Labor'' and ''Service'' types multiplied by their quantities.{br}
If the standard cost method is used for the stock kit, any difference between the currently effective standard cost and the total cost of components is recorded (as with non-stock kits) to the Standard Cost Variance account determined by the posting class of the stock kit.{br}
When a stock kit is disassembled, the costs of its stock components, which are returned to inventory, are calculated depending on the valuation method of the components as follows:[anchor|#ul_txg_lkh_yx] *''Average'': The cost of the component is calculated based on the setting of the '''Avg. Default Returns Cost''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form. By default, this setting is the average cost of the item at the warehouse. You can also select the last cost as the value of this box. *''FIFO'': The cost of the component is calculated based on the setting of the '''FIFO Default Returns Cost''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form. By default, this setting is the average cost of the item at the warehouse. You can also select the last cost as the value of this box. *''Specific'': The cost of the component is the average cost of the item at the warehouse. If there is no average cost of the item at the warehouse, the last cost of the item at the warehouse is used. *''Standard'': The cost of the component is the standard cost of the item at the warehouse, if any standard cost is defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. Otherwise, the global standard cost of the item defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form is used.
==Lot and Serial Numbers for Kits== If component parts as well as assembled kits have lot or serial numbers, your company will know precisely which assembled kits contain any component, if this information is requested by the component manufacturer. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Accounting_for_Kits|Inventory Item Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Assemble_Stock_Kit|To Assemble a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Stock_Kit|To Create a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Disassemble_Stock_Kit|To Disassemble a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] ([~/?ScreenId=IN307000|IN307000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_10|Sales Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202010|AR202010]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000])

A non-stock kit is a bundle of stock and non-stock components; you assign an individual inventory identifier to the non-stock kit, and it can be selected in sales orders. Non-stock kits are virtual kits because they neither produced nor tracked in inventory, unlike stock kits. The stock components of the non-stock kit remain in inventory and can be sold in the kit or as separate units.{br}
In this topic, you will read about the configuration, processing, and cost calculation of non-stock kits.{br}{TOC}[anchor|#nonstockkits] ==Configuration of Non-Stock Kits== When you create a non-stock kit, you do the following:[anchor|#_a8651c20-e547-4259-8087-5559ccb78e43] #If you need to create a number of kits with similar settings, you create an item class for each group of kits by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form. #You create as many kits as you need by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form. To indicate that an item is a kit, you select the '''Is a Kit''' check box on the '''General Settings''' tab of this form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Non_Stock_Kit|To Create a Non-Stock Kit]. #You create a specification for each kit by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500]) form. In the specification, you select the inventory items that will be included in the kit and specify the settings of each component. Any lot- and serial-tracked stock items can be added to the specification of a non-stock kit, except for items with the ''When Used'' assignment method or with the ''User-Enterable'' issue method specified for their lot/serial classes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000]) form. For details on this step, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Non_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Non-Stock Kit]. #You assign sales prices to kits as follows: #*If you sell a limited number of kits, you assign the default prices on a per-kit basis by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form. #*If you are selling more than ten kits, you assign multiple sales prices to kits by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_10|Sales Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202010|AR202010]) form.
==Processing of Non-Stock Kits == As with non-stock items, non-stock kits are not stocked. When non-stock kits are added to a sales order, the items are gathered for the sale but no preliminary assembly has been performed. When a non-stock kit is listed on a sales order as a line item, its stock components are specified on a pick list and shipped to the customer. Upon shipment confirmation, the quantity of stock components is decreased while the quantities of non-stock components and kits are not tracked in any way.{br}
On release of a Sales Order invoice for a non-stock kit with stock components, the system generates an inventory issue; on release of the inventory issue, the system debits the COGS accounts of the stock components, thus updating the stock components&rsquo; costs. On the sale of a non-stock kit with only non-stock components, no inventory issue is generated.{br}
When you process a sale of a non-stock kit, its stock components are issued from inventory, and the sales revenue from all components of the kit is recorded to accounts.{br}
For a non-stock kit that includes stock components for which the '''Divisible Unit''' check box is cleared for base UOMs on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form, when a user creates and saves a shipment for a sales order with at least one such kit, the system validates the quantity of each component included in the specified quantity of the kit, making sure that it is an integer. If the quantity of any component is not an integer, the system displays an error message. The shipment is not created or is created but placed on hold, depending on the state of the '''Hold Shipments on Entry''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000]) form. When a user creates and saves a receipt for a purchase order that includes at least one non-stock kit with similar stock components, the system works similarly. ==Calculation of Cost for Non-Stock Kits== The cost of a non-stock kit may include the cost of the kit itself and the costs of all stock components included in the kit. You can select one of the following cost calculation rules on in the '''Cost Calculation Basis for Non-Stock Kits''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000]) form:[anchor|#_0a245417-0290-4289-b75e-38c12b9f6352] *''Stock Component Cost'': The system will use the sum of the costs of the kit&rsquo;s stock components as the cost of a non-stock kit. You can select this rule if the kit does not include non-stock components or the value of the included non-stock components is very low. *''Non-Stock Kit Standard Cost'': The system will use the standard current cost of the non-stock kit. You can select this rule if the kit does not include stock components or the value of the included stock components is very low. *''Non-Stock Kit Standard Cost Plus Stock Component Cost'': The system will calculate the sum of the standard current cost of a non-stock kit and the costs of the stock components of this kit.
You can enter the kit standard cost directly in the '''Pending Cost''' box on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form when you create or modify the non-stock kit.((({S:Warn}Only the ''Standard Cost'' valuation method may be assigned to non-stock kits. For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods]. ))) ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000])

