The physical inventory process in a particular warehouse includes the following stages:[anchor|#ol_h15_c22_rj] *Physical inventory preparation *Counting of items *Entry of counting data *Adjustment generation
These stages are described in detail in the following sections, along with other key information about physical inventory counts.{br}{TOC}[anchor|#_c47e0a7e-5101-46fd-a6bb-073831910ec7] ==Physical Inventory Preparation==((({S:Warn}Before you prepare any physical counts, make sure that all inventory documents have been released. ))) You generate a physical inventory document by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_40_00|Prepare Physical Count] ([~/?ScreenId=IN504000|IN504000]) form. On this form, you select the appropriate physical inventory type for the count.{br}
For the physical inventory, you can select a particular warehouse and locations on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_40_00|Prepare Physical Count] form only if the warehouse is not associated with the physical inventory type. Once you are done making selections on the selection tabs of this form, you click '''Generate PI''' on the form toolbar. The system generates a physical inventory document, which you can view on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) form, with the ''Counting in Progress'' status. The system assigns the document a reference number in accordance with the numbering sequence assigned to physical inventories on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form.((({S:Warn}Starting at the moment when the physical inventory document is generated, no inventory transactions (issues, receipts, or transfers) are allowed that involve items included in the list, meaning that this inventory is in a frozen state. You can view the list of items involved in counting by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_90_00|Physical Inventory Locked Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN409000|IN409000]) form. ))) The generated physical inventory document contains the list of items for counting, arranged to the specifications on the '''Assignment Order''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_89_00|Physical Inventory Types] form. For each stock item included in the count, the document may have one line or multiple lines, depending on how many warehouse locations are used to store the item and whether the item has subitems or lot or serial numbers. In the simplest case—when such features as ''Inventory Subitems'', ''Lot or Serial Tracking'', and ''Multiple Warehouse Locations'' are not enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form—a line identifies an item available in the warehouse with its book quantity.{br}
You can export the list of items for counting to an Excel file by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] form. Alternatively, you can use the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_62_05_00|Physical Count Sheets] ([~/?ScreenId=IN620500|IN620500]) report to print item lists (count sheets) for distribution to all employees involved in counting. If you want to prevent employees from reusing the book quantity of items as the physical quantity instead of actually counting the items, you can hide the '''Book Qty.''' column from the printed count sheets by selecting the '''Hide Book Qty.''' check box in the report parameters.{br}
For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Preparation_for_Physical_Count|Preparation for Physical Count].[anchor|#_a9ad80d3-f72e-4341-9263-333405393080] ==Counting of Items== Employees involved in physical inventory can start counting items after you distribute count sheets and count tags (if you use tags in physical counting) to the employees. The counting process includes the following steps:[anchor|#_7a30361d-93f3-4154-911c-7fd79e0895b3] #Employees count the actual quantity of an item with the properties specified in the line (the specific inventory ID, lot or serial number, and warehouse location). #Employees specify the quantity in the appropriate line of the count sheet. #You indicate to the system that the counting process is finished by clicking '''Finish Counting''' on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) form for the current count. On this form, you can see that the system has changed the status of the physical inventory document to ''Data Entering''.
After the counting process is finished,you can start entering counting data into the system.{br}
Acumatica ERP provides you with ability to automate counting by using barcode scanners or mobile devices with barcode scanning support. For details, see [HelpRoot_WMS\WMS_Scan_and_Count_GeneralInfo|Counting in Physical Inventory: General Information].[anchor|#_992b7a9a-11c3-45fd-b593-9cc681a1bbb5] ==Entry of Counting Data== The process of entering counting data includes the following steps:[anchor|#_f8f8cca2-d0dc-4ee9-ae01-d8b2ac2c6303] #Employees enter the counting data into the system manually or you import data from Excel spreadsheets, depending on the type of count sheets the employees used for counting. #You review the data entered into the system after all lines have been entered. #You complete the physical inventory process or cancel the process, depending on the entered data. ((({S:Warn}No movement of goods is allowed and no inventory transactions are released during the entry of the counting data if the '''Unfreeze Stock When Counting Is Finished''' check box is cleared for the physical inventory type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_89_00|Physical Inventory Types] ([~/?ScreenId=IN208900|IN208900]) form. In this case, the inventory is frozen until data entry is completed. ))) Manual data entry can be performed as follows. Multiple employees participating in counting can enter count data line by line simultaneously from different locations by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_10|Physical Inventory Count] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305010|IN305010]) form. Each line of the physical inventory document has its own status, and as count data is entered, the status of the line changes from ''Not Entered'' to ''Entered''. Once an employee enters the actual quantity in a line on this form, this data is committed to the database so the data can be visible to other users who are entering the data and to you if you are viewing the count data on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) form. For details about the entry process, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Enter_Count_Data|To Enter the Count Data].{br}
Employees can simultaneously enter their count data from their computers by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_10|Physical Inventory Count] form. Once the user finishes the row on this form, the system commits the data to the database—all the quantities entered by multiple users will be summed up for each combination of inventory ID, subitem, warehouse location, and lot or serial number. This makes the most recently entered data immediately visible to all users who may be simultaneously using this form for data entry.{br}
If employees find items that are not listed in the count sheets, and the count sheets contain empty lines, these items must be entered into the system, as described in [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Enter_Count_Data_for_New_Items|To Enter the Count Data for New Items].{br}
To import the count data from an Excel spreadsheet, you can use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] form. For a physical count with the ''Data Entering'' status on this form, you can upload the file to the system, review the data on the form, and save the results to the database. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Import_Count_Data|To Import the Count Data From an Excel Spreadsheet].{br}
If all the lines of the document have the ''Entered'' status, you can complete the counting. You can cancel the physical inventory if you cannot complete it for some reason. If there is no valid data for some of the lines, you can set the count values to 0 or change the line status from ''Not Entered'' to ''Skipped'' and complete counting. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Enter_Count_Data|To Enter the Count Data].{br}
Once the entered data is verified, you can indicate to the system that the data entry phase is completed by clicking '''Complete PI''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review]. This changes the status of the physical inventory document to ''Completed''. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Complete_PI_Count|To Complete the Physical Inventory Count].{br}
Completing or canceling the physical inventory unfreezes the inventory items involved in the count.[anchor|#_987bcfbe-1bd7-4335-b7c7-07665f779acf] ==Adjustment Generation== If the '''Release PI Adjustment Automatically''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form, when you complete the physical inventory, the system changes the status of the physical inventory document to ''Completed'' and generates the inventory adjustments to correct the on-hand quantities. An adjustment is generated for each item with a nonzero quantity variance, including the items with no associated transactions. The system uses the current costs of the items to calculate the cost variance. The reference numbers of these documents are displayed on the '''Adjustment Info''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) form; the status of these documents is ''Balanced''. You can review the generated adjustments on the '''Adjustments''' tab of this form.{br}
If the '''Release PI Adjustment Automatically''' check box is cleared, the system works as follows:[anchor|#ul_q5p_r2v_zgb] *When you click '''Complete PI''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] form, the physical inventory document has the ''In Review'' status and an adjustment is created with the ''Balanced'' status on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_30_00|Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=IN303000|IN303000]) form. *In the adjustment on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_30_00|Adjustments] form, you can edit the value of the '''Unit Cost''' column for particular items if the value of the '''Quantity''' column is positive for the item. When you manually change the unit cost and save the edited adjustment, the system changes the value of the '''Final Ext. Variance Cost''' column in the item line of the physical inventory document on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] form. *You can delete an adjustment before the adjustment is released. After the adjustment is deleted, the status of the physical inventory document changes to ''Data Entering'' on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] form. You can edit the physical inventory document and then create a new adjustment. *When you successfully release an adjustment on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_30_00|Adjustments] form, the system updates the values of the '''Final Ext. Variance Cost''' column in the item line of the physical inventory document and changes the status of the physical inventory document to ''Completed'' on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] form.
==Cost Calculation After Counting== The system specifies values in the '''Unit Cost''' and '''Estimated Ext. Variance Cost''' columns on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) form when you click '''Finish Counting''' on the form toolbar. The system also updates these columns when users change the physical quantity while entering data.{br}
For lines with a positive variance quantity, the system calculates the values of the '''Unit Cost''' and '''Estimated Ext. Variance Cost''' columns based on the rules of the valuation methods specified for items as follows:[anchor|#ul_cf4_cz3_ygb] *For the ''FIFO'' and ''Average'' valuation methods: **The unit cost is calculated based on the values of the '''FIFO Default Returns Cost''' box (for the'' FIFO'' valuation method) or the '''Avg. Default Returns Cost''' box (for the ''Average'' valuation method) specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form. **If the average cost of the item is zero on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form, the system uses the value of the '''Last Cost''' box on this form as the unit cost. **If both the average cost and the last cost are zero on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] form, the system uses the average cost on the '''Price/Cost Info''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form as the unit cost. If the average cost is zero, the system uses the last cost on the same tab as the unit cost. *For the ''Specific'' valuation method: **The system uses the cost layer that corresponds to the item as the unit cost. If multiple cost layers exist for the item, the system uses the last created cost layer as the unit cost. **If no cost layers exist for an item with a specific lot or serial number, the system uses the last cost specified on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] form as the unit cost. *For the ''Standard'' valuation method: **The system uses the current standard cost specified in the '''Standard Cost''' section of the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] form as the unit cost. **If the current standard cost is zero, the system uses the current standard cost on the '''Price/Cost Info''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form as the unit cost.
For lines with a negative variance quantity, the system calculates the values of the '''Unit Cost''' and '''Estimated Ext. Variance Cost''' columns based on the calculation rule of the adjustment; the system uses the data of the current cost layer for these calculations.{br}
The '''Update Actual Cost''' action recalculates the values of the '''Unit Cost''', '''Estimated Ext. Variance Cost''', and '''Total Variance Cost''' columns for lines with a negative variance quantity based on the calculation rule of the PI adjustment, and the system uses the data of the current cost layer. For lines with a positive variance quantity, this action recalculates the costs if the default costs were changed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] form. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Planning_for_Physical_Inventory|Configuration of Physical Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Preparation_for_Physical_Count|Preparation for Physical Count] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_The_Cost_of_Inventory|The Cost of Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Enter_Count_Data|To Enter the Count Data] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Enter_Count_Data_for_New_Items|To Enter the Count Data for New Items] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Import_Count_Data|To Import the Count Data From an Excel Spreadsheet] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Complete_PI_Count|To Complete the Physical Inventory Count] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_10|Physical Inventory Count] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305010|IN305010]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_40_00|Prepare Physical Count] ([~/?ScreenId=IN504000|IN504000])

When you decide to perform a physical inventory, you must prepare for this process appropriately. As a result of the preparation, you generate a physical inventory document (count sheet) and distribute it among the employees who will perform the inventory.{br}
When you are preparing for a physical inventory, you perform the following steps:[anchor|#_be190556-e8ad-414b-a584-c0045ab704ca] #At the warehouse, you organize the goods to prepare for counting, and you complete data entry related to normal warehouse activities that are not connected to the physical inventory. For details, see [[#_9c2ee11b-ce1f-4329-ace5-4f901a0212a4|Organizing Goods in a Warehouse and Preparing Book Quantities]. #You prepare accurate book quantities in the system, as described in [[#_9c2ee11b-ce1f-4329-ace5-4f901a0212a4|Organizing Goods in a Warehouse and Preparing Book Quantities]. #You create the count review document (count sheet) of the needed physical inventory type. For details, see [[#_42a06e26-3687-4016-898e-5ad02423a992|Creating and Distributing a Count Sheet]. #Optional: You add new lines to a prepared count sheet if you realize that the quantity of some stock items became nonzero after completing data entry related to normal warehouse activities. For more information, see [[#_051f8e6c-64e4-4a24-9f4c-d19658c93384|Adding New Lines to a Prepared Count Review Document]. #Optional: You prepare tag sheets. For details, [[#_4a03ef61-09ba-41f9-9a9a-5503a08660f7|Using Tags in Counting].
In this topic, you will find detailed information about the preparation process.{br}{TOC}[anchor|#_9c2ee11b-ce1f-4329-ace5-4f901a0212a4] ==Organizing Goods in a Warehouse and Preparing Book Quantities== When you prepare for a physical inventory in your warehouse, you do the following:[anchor|#_4834bd46-c57c-44ea-9faf-b1e82e003ef8] *You oversee the employees in organizing the goods at the warehouse to be able to count accurate physical quantities that match the book quantities. All goods should be placed in appropriate locations. *You enter and release all inventory transactions that have been physically performed at the warehouse and have already affected the physical quantity. *You process or delete any unreleased documents in the system, which you can find by clicking '''Unreleased Documents''' on the toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_90_00|Close Financial Periods] ([~/?ScreenId=IN509000|IN509000]) form after you select financial periods. {br}
The system produces the book quantity for physical counts as follows:{{{{(Book Qty) = (Qty on Hand) – (Qty on SO Shipped) }}}} The formula elements mean the following:{br}
{{Book Qty}}: The physical count book quantity{br}
{{Qty on Hand}}: The quantity of items on hand{br}
{{Qty on SO Shipped}}: The quantity of items on sales orders that have been shipped{br}
You have to exclude some items from the physical count because they are not reflected in the book quantity that is printed in the count review document (and used for comparison with the physical quantity). For example, you can place those items in a certain location in the warehouse, label the location to be certain the items will not be counted inadvertently, and skip the counting of this location. You have to make sure those items won&rsquo;t be mistakenly counted; otherwise, there could be an incorrect difference between the book quantity and physical quantity in the count review document.{br}
You have to exclude the following items from the physical count:[anchor|#ul_qjg_zyy_zs] *Items that have been received to the warehouse if the receipts cannot be released in the system at the moment *Items on unreleased inventory issues and not-yet-issued shipments if these items haven&rsquo;t been removed from the warehouse yet [anchor|#_42a06e26-3687-4016-898e-5ad02423a992] ==Creating and Distributing a Count Sheet== For every physical count that is performed at the warehouse, you have to create the count review document that is used for processing the count result. On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_40_00|Prepare Physical Count] ([~/?ScreenId=IN504000|IN504000]) form, you can review the count lines that will be included in the count review document and initiate the process of creating the document. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Prepare_PI_Count|To Prepare a Physical Inventory Count].{br}
After you select the physical count type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_40_00|Prepare Physical Count] form, a preview of the count lines with the tag numbers (if you use tags) is displayed that will be generated for the physical count iteration. Before you start the counting process, you can review the count lines to make sure the needed items are selected for counting and the order of count lines is as expected.{br}
After you have verified the count lines, on the form toolbar, you click '''Generate PI''' to prepare the count review document and start the counting process in the system. Starting at this moment, transactional activities should be frozen at the warehouse and the processing of inventory transactions must be paused in the system until the physical count is complete.{br}
When you click '''Generate PI''', the system performs the following actions:[anchor|#ul_hdq_tsj_xs] *Generates the count review document that consists of the count lines, which should be populated with physical quantities. The system opens the count review document on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) form with the ''Counting in Progress'' status. *:((({S:Warn}You can create the count review document directly on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] form by clicking '''Add New Record''' on the form toolbar without first previewing the count on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_40_00|Prepare Physical Count] form. Regardless of how you generated the count review document, if you notice that it is wrong, you can click '''Cancel PI''' on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] form, make the necessary changes, and create the count review document again. ))) *Generates the count sheets, which can be printed by using the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_62_05_00|Physical Count Sheets] ([~/?ScreenId=IN620500|IN620500]) report, as described in [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Print_Count_Sheets|To Print Count Sheets]. *:Alternatively, you can export the count review document to a Microsoft Excel spreadsheet (see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Export_Count_Sheet_to_Excel|To Export a Count Sheet to an Excel Spreadsheet]) if your organization uses non-paper processesfor counting. *Generates the count tags, which can be printed by using the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_62_10_00|Physical Count Tags] ([~/?ScreenId=IN621000|IN621000]) report. The tags will be generated if the '''Use Tags''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] form at the moment. For details about how to print tag sheets, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Print_Tags|To Print Tags]. *Freezes the release of inventory transactions for the warehouse being counted. Under the ''Full Physical Inventory'' method, the system doesn&rsquo;t allow the release of any inventory transactions for the warehouse. For other physical count methods, the system doesn&rsquo;t release inventory transactions if they include items that are currently being counted at the warehouse. The system continues to freeze inventory transactions while the count review document has the ''Counting in Progress'' status.
In a count sheet, the items are arranged according to the settings on the '''Assignment Order''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_89_00|Physical Inventory Types] ([~/?ScreenId=IN208900|IN208900]) form. For each inventory item included in the count, the document may have one line or multiple lines, depending on how many locations are used to store the item and whether the item has subitems or lot or serial numbers. For items with serial numbers assigned, a separate line is generated for each serial number.{br}
If the '''Use Tags''' option is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] form, the count sheet includes tag numbers for each line generated.[anchor|#_051f8e6c-64e4-4a24-9f4c-d19658c93384] ==Adding New Lines to a Prepared Count Review Document== When the count review document is prepared, the system adds to the count review document (count sheet) only those inventory items that have a nonzero booked quantity. Thus, if you have prepared the count sheet and then the quantity of some inventory items that are not in the sheet has changed from zero to a nonzero quantity (due to items being found or received), you may need to add new count lines to the count sheet. On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) form, you can add a new line to a prepared count sheet as long as you adhere to the following rules:[anchor|#ul_egs_tnw_kbb] *The location and warehouse that you specify in this line must match the location and warehouse selection criteria of the count sheet to which you are adding a line. *You cannot add a line if the specified combination of inventory ID, location, and warehouse is already included in this physical inventory count. *You cannot add a line if the specified combination of inventory ID, location, and warehouse is included in any other physical inventory count that currently is in progress. *The item that you specify in this line must correspond to criteria of the physical inventory type which this physical inventory count is prepared. For example, if you count physical inventory by ABC code, the item should be assigned the ABC code selected in the settings of the physical inventory type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_89_00|Physical Inventory Types] ([~/?ScreenId=IN208900|IN208900]) form. (This restriction applies to all physical inventory types except for those that have the ''Full Physical Inventory'' generation method.)
After you have added any new lines and saved your changes, no inventory transactions (issues, receipts, or transfers) are allowed for the added inventory items in the specified location and warehouse.[anchor|#_4a03ef61-09ba-41f9-9a9a-5503a08660f7] ==Using Tags in Counting== Tags may or may not be used in the counting process, depending on your organization&rsquo;s policies for physical inventory counts. A tag count is useful for a full-scale end-of-year physical inventory.{br}
You can use tags in counts if the '''Use Tags''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. With this check box selected, the system assigns a tag number to each line of the count sheets when you prepare the physical inventory count. Depending on the features enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, each tag can contain the following information:[anchor|#ul_jvj_qst_fs] *Tag number *Inventory ID *Subitem (if the ''Inventory Subitems'' feature is enabled) *Lot or serial number (if the ''Lot and Serial Tracking'' feature is enabled) *Warehouse location (if the ''Multiple Warehouse Locations'' feature is enabled) *The book quantity of the item with these properties {br}
You can print tags by using the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_62_10_00|Physical Count Tags] ([~/?ScreenId=IN621000|IN621000]) report, as described in [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Print_Tags|To Print Tags]. The tags can be distributed (in accordance with the count sheets) among employees who are participating in the count. Tags can be used for recording the results of the actual counting and for entering the count results when the counting stage is completed. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Planning_for_Physical_Inventory|Configuration of Physical Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Physical_Inventory_Counts|Physical Inventory Counts] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__How_Prepare_PI_Count|To Prepare a Physical Inventory Count] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Export_Count_Sheet_to_Excel|To Export a Count Sheet to an Excel Spreadsheet] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Print_Count_Sheets|To Print Count Sheets] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Print_Tags|To Print Tags]

To prepare for a physical inventory (PI) count, you need to print count sheets and make the system freeze the items involved in the count—that is, the system should not release any transactions that involve these items until the count is completed.{br}
You generate a count sheet by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_40_00|Prepare Physical Count] ([~/?ScreenId=IN504000|IN504000]) form, as described in this topic.[anchor|#_de51ea77-4083-4b04-9b2b-a77157bb4fde]((({S:Hint}To open any form, you can navigate to it or search for it (by its name or by its form ID without periods). For more information about search capabilities, see [HelpRoot_Interface\UIG__con_New_UI_Search|Search]. ))) ==Before You Proceed==[anchor|#ol_i3t_pz5_xl] #Open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_89_00|Physical Inventory Types] ([~/?ScreenId=IN208900|IN208900]) form by searching for or navigating to it. #Make sure that the physical inventory type you are going to use has been created on this form. #On the '''Assignment Order''' tab, review the assignment order to be used on the count sheets, and make changes if needed for the current count.
==To Prepare a Physical Inventory Count==[anchor|#_2e4234cd-e500-4b63-8ebf-5caf14598aed] #Open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_40_00|Prepare Physical Count] ([~/?ScreenId=IN504000|IN504000]) form. #In the '''Type ID''' box of the '''Preview''' tab, select the appropriate physical inventory type for counting. #If the '''Warehouse''' box is not filled in, select the warehouse in which the count should be performed. You can select a particular warehouse only if the physical inventory type is not intended for a particular warehouse. #On the form toolbar, click '''Generate PI'''. #:The system generates the physical inventory document and opens the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_50_00|Physical Inventory Review] ([~/?ScreenId=IN305000|IN305000]) form, which displays the document. #Review the list of items to be counted, and edit the list if needed. #If you have made changes to the list, on the form toolbar, click '''Save'''.

The closing of financial periods in the Inventory module is a technical procedure that you must perform before closing the same period in the General Ledger module. You close financial periods to prevent users from posting transactions to these periods.{br}
In this chapter, you will find information about specifics of closing periods in the Inventory module. ==In This Section==[anchor|#_10e2aeba-7653-4bd3-8be1-2314952d4a0f] {| class="checklist invisiblechecklist" | width="100%" |- | [anchor|#_971d1ef1-db04-4805-a808-6d3874af31b4] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Financial_Period_Closing_Inventory|Financial Period Closing in the Inventory Module] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Reconciliation_IN_Account_GL_Account|Reconciliation of the Cost of Inventory with the Account Balance]
| [anchor|#_b69888d6-595c-47d4-a289-e7d61c2cca21] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Review_Unprocessed_Inventory_Transactions|To Review Unprocessed Inventory Transactions] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Close_Financial_Period|To Close Financial Periods in Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__HOW_To_Reopen_Financial_Period_in_IN|To Reopen a Financial Period in Inventory]
|}

If your organization prepares financial reports on a regular basis, accountants should close financial periods in all modules that your organization uses in Acumatica ERP. Before the reports can be prepared for a financial period, the accountants have to verify the account balances, process all necessary transactions for the period, and then close the financial period for further transaction processing.{br}
In this topic, you will read about the process of closing financial periods in Inventory. ==Closing Financial Periods in Inventory== Closing a financial period in a module is a technical procedure that prevents the posting of new transactions from this module to the closed period, which is undesirable or might be even forbidden after all figures have been verified and disclosed in the reports.{br}
The closed periods cannot be selected in the '''Post Period''' box on inventory transaction data entry forms. However, a closed period can be typed manually in a transaction and the inventory transaction can still be processed to the period if the '''Restrict Access to Closed Periods''' check box is cleared on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_10_20_00|General Ledger Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=GL102000|GL102000]) form. The '''Restrict Access to Closed Periods''' setting applies to the transactions that are produced by all modules that post transactions to the General Ledger module. Only users assigned to the ''Financial Supervisor'' role on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form can post transactions to closed periods; this is the case even when the '''Restrict Access to Closed Periods''' check box is selected.{br}
Closing a financial period in the Inventory module includes the following procedures:[anchor|#ul_wvv_tg4_dt] *Inventory clerks count the physical inventory, and the warehouse manager makes the necessary inventory adjustments to make the book quantities of items equal to the physical quantities of items in the warehouse. For details on physical inventory counting, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Physical_Inventory_Counts|Physical Inventory Counts]. *The warehouse manager verifies and processes the necessary inventory transactions for the period. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Review_Unprocessed_Inventory_Transactions|To Review Unprocessed Inventory Transactions]. *The accountant reconciles the inventory account balance in the Inventory and General Ledger modules for the period. For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Reconciliation_IN_Account_GL_Account|Reconciliation of the Cost of Inventory with the Account Balance]. *The accountant closes the financial period in the Inventory module. During the process of closing the period, the system verifies that there are no unprocessed inventory transactions entered for these periods, and marks the periods as closed in the Inventory module. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Close_Financial_Period|To Close Financial Periods in Inventory].
After the financial period is closed in all modules, the accountant can prepare the financial reports. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Financials\Finance_ClosingPeriods_GeneralInfo|Closing Financial Periods: General Information] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Reconciliation_IN_Account_GL_Account|Reconciliation of the Cost of Inventory with the Account Balance] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Review_Unprocessed_Inventory_Transactions|To Review Unprocessed Inventory Transactions] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Close_Financial_Period|To Close Financial Periods in Inventory]

You can reconcile the inventory account balance by comparing the account balance calculated by inventory transactions with the account balance calculated by General Ledger transactions. If you discover a mismatch, each transaction has to be carefully reviewed in the Inventory and General Ledger modules, and corrective actions have to be made to eliminate the mismatch. Reconciliation is a recommended practice before period closing to verify the account balance and the transactions in the inventory account.{br}
In this topic, you will find recommendations for performing reconciliation of the inventory account balance with the General Ledger account balance in Acumatica ERP and the list of forms and report you can use for reconciliation. For simplicity, the topic describes the reconciliation process for only one inventory account. If you have multiple accounts, you can repeat the procedure for each inventory account.{br}{TOC} ==Reconciliation Process in Inventory== Before starting reconciliation, you must you must decide which periods you want to close. In Acumatica ERP, you reconcile the inventory account balance for the ''last activity period'' (that is, the period when the last transaction was performed) and the ''historical periods'' (that is, the periods that precede the last activity period) separately. For the last activity period, the inventory account balance equals the cost of the inventory on hand.{br}
In Acumatica ERP, you do the following to reconcile the balance of an inventory account in the Inventory and General Ledger modules:[anchor|#_6fc9de40-181b-461f-b2bd-db80a168f6d5] #You reconcile the balance of the inventory account for the historical periods, as described in [[#_7385631f-858e-4029-95dd-796b543341aa|Reconciliation of the Inventory Account Balance for Historical Periods]. #You reconcile the balance of the inventory account for the last activity period, as described in [[#_f0d77834-bff7-443d-9403-2bafe45fe193|Reconciliation of the Inventory Account Balance for the Last Activity Period]. #If the balances of the inventory and General Ledger accounts disagree, you investigate the reasons. For details, see [[#section_ky1_rmb_2t|Investigation of a Disagreement Between the Balances].
For the list of Acumatica ERP forms and reports you can use in the reconciliation process, see [[#_eb01d874-4c04-4665-88ba-0ae3880b102b|Reports and Forms Used for Reconciliation in the Inventory module].[anchor|#_7385631f-858e-4029-95dd-796b543341aa] ==Reconciliation of the Inventory Account Balance for Historical Periods== You reconcile the balance of an inventory account for a historical period as follows:[anchor|#_e7919e71-f68d-4125-b905-19981ec8e8b6] #You find the ending balance of the account in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_70_00|Historical Inventory Valuation] ([~/?ScreenId=IN617000|IN617000]) report as follows: ##You run the report with the following parameters: ##*'''Format''': ''Summary'' ##* '''Start Period''': The historical period ##*'''End Period''': The historical period ##:((({S:Warn}If you want to review the account balance for multiple historical periods, in the '''Start Period''' box, you select the earliest period, and in the '''End Period''' box, you select the latest period. ))) ##In the '''Account/Subaccount Ending Balance''' line of the report, you find the ending balance of the account, which you reconcile, and record the balance. #Optional: You review the inventory transactions and the ending balance of the inventory account on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_30_00|Inventory Transactions by Account] ([~/?ScreenId=IN403000|IN403000]) form as follows: ##In the Summary area of the form, you do the following: ##*In the '''Inventory Account''' box, you select the inventory account for which you want to review transactions. ##*In the '''Period''' box, you select the historical period. ##*You select the '''By Financial Period''' check box to filter the transactions by post period. ##In the '''Ending Balance''' column of the last table row, you find the ending balance for the inventory account and compare it with the balance found in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_70_00|Historical Inventory Valuation] report. The balances should be the same. #You find the ending balance of the inventory account in the General Ledger by using the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\GL_63_20_00|Trial Balance Summary] ([~/?ScreenId=GL632000|GL632000]) report as follows: ##You run the report with the following parameters: ##*'''Ledger ID''': Select the ledger with the ''Actual'' type. ##*'''Financial Period''': Select the same historical period, for which you retrieved data from the Inventory module. ##In the '''Ending Balance''' column for the inventory account, you find the ending balance. #You compare the ending balance in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_70_00|Historical Inventory Valuation] report with the balance in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\GL_63_20_00|Trial Balance Summary] report. You can receive one of the following results: #*The balances agree: This means that the inventory account balance is reconciled for the selected period. You can start reconciling the same account for another historical period or for the last activity period, if the account balance is reconciled for all historical periods. #*The balances disagree: You investigate the reasons, as described in [[#section_ky1_rmb_2t|Investigation of a Disagreement Between the Balances], and reconcile the account balance once again. [anchor|#_f0d77834-bff7-443d-9403-2bafe45fe193] ==Reconciliation of the Inventory Account Balance for the Last Activity Period== After you have reconciled the balance of an inventory account for historical periods, you can start reconciling the balance of this account for the last activity period as follows:[anchor|#_ee8305c7-fa27-4a33-ae0f-71912c657db4] #You find the ending balance for the account in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_55_00|Inventory Valuation] ([~/?ScreenId=IN615500|IN615500]) report as follows: ##You run the report with ''Summary'' selected in the '''Format''' box. ##In the '''Total''' line of the report, you find the '''Total Cost''' value, which is the ending balance of the inventory account for the last activity period. You keep this value for further comparison. #Optional: You review the inventory transactions and the ending balance of the inventory account on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_30_00|Inventory Transactions by Account] ([~/?ScreenId=IN403000|IN403000]) form as follows: ##In the Summary area of the form, you do the following: ##*In the '''Inventory Account''' box, you select the inventory account for which you want to review transactions. ##*In the '''Period''' box, you select the last activity period. ##*You select the '''By Financial Period''' check box to filter the transactions by post period. ##In the '''Ending Balance''' column of the last table row, you find the ending balance for the inventory account and compare it with the balance found in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_55_00|Inventory Valuation] report. The balances should be the same. #You find the ending balance of the inventory account in the General Ledger by using the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\GL_63_20_00|Trial Balance Summary] ([~/?ScreenId=GL632000|GL632000]) report as follows: ##You run the report with the following parameters: ##*'''Ledger ID''': Select the ledger with the ''Actual'' type. ##*'''Financial Period''': Select the last activity period. ##In the '''Ending Balance''' column for the inventory account, you find the ending balance. #You compare the ending balance you found in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_55_00|Inventory Valuation] report with the balance found in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\GL_63_20_00|Trial Balance Summary] report. You can receive one of the following results: #*The balances agree: This means that the inventory account balance is reconciled for the last activity period. Now you can close these financial periods in the Inventory module; for details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Close_Financial_Period|To Close Financial Periods in Inventory]. #*The balances disagree: You investigate the reasons, as described in [[#section_ky1_rmb_2t|Investigation of a Disagreement Between the Balances], and reconcile the account balance once again. [anchor|#section_ky1_rmb_2t] ==Investigation of a Disagreement Between the Balances == If the balances don&rsquo;t agree, you have to review every transaction in the Inventory and General Ledger modules to find the entries that do not match. You do the following:[anchor|#_ad9cde9d-c65f-4434-9fba-aff730b24f1f] #Verify that all inventory transactions are posted in the General Ledger module by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_30_00|Inventory Transactions by Account] ([~/?ScreenId=IN403000|IN403000]) form. If there is an inventory transaction that is missing in the General Ledger account on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_40_40_00|Account Details] ([~/?ScreenId=GL404000|GL404000]) form, you can do any of the following: #*Review the inventory transaction and make sure the General Ledger transaction has been generated for it. The transactions could be not generated if the '''Update GL''' check box was cleared when the inventory transaction was released. #*Review the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_50_20_00|Post Transactions] ([~/?ScreenId=GL502000|GL502000]) form to see if there are any ''Unposted'' batches of journal transactions. Process the needed transactions to eliminate the discrepancy. #Check whether there are any transactions posted to the inventory account by other modules by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_40_40_00|Account Details] form. If there is a General Ledger transaction that is missing on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_30_00|Inventory Transactions by Account] form, open the batch of journal transactions and find the source document for it. Depending on the reason the General Ledger entry has been directly processed to the inventory account without the processing from the Inventory module, you can either correct the General Ledger transaction or process the missing inventory transaction in the Inventory module and reverse the generated batch to equate the balance of the inventory account in the modules. ((({S:Warn}If the '''Post Option''' is set to ''Detail'' for an inventory account on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_20_25_00|Chart of Accounts] ([~/?ScreenId=GL202500|GL202500]) form, detailed journal entries are posted to the inventory account regardless of the Inventory module settings, and the General Ledger entries in the inventory account on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_40_40_00|Account Details] form can be matched one to one to the transaction lines on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_30_00|Inventory Transactions by Account] form. Otherwise, if the summary posting to the inventory account is configured for the General Ledger module, a number of inventory transaction lines will correspond to one summarized General Ledger entry. If you use summary posting to an inventory account in the General Ledger, we recommend that you specify unique sequence numbers for different inventory transaction types, so that you can group the inventory transaction lines by transaction type and reference number and match them one to one to the summarized General Ledger entries in the inventory account, if needed. ))) After you have investigated the reasons for the disagreement, you can recalculate the balance of the inventory account, as described in the next section, to view changes in transactions on Inventory forms and reports.[anchor|#section_kpd_yz1_2t] ==Recalculation of the Inventory Account Balance== You can run the inventory validation process on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_50_00|Validate Inventory] ([~/?ScreenId=IN505000|IN505000]) form to recalculate the inventory account balance for periods after you have corrected inventory transactions. (This process doesn't affect the on-hand quantity of items in inventory, because this quantity is updated with every released inventory transaction and tracked separately from the inventory account balance.) The inventory validation process performs the following operations:[anchor|#ol_h4l_qbb_2t] #Recalculates the available quantity and the subtotals by allocation type that are stored in the database and that you can view on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_10_00|Inventory Summary] ([~/?ScreenId=IN401000|IN401000]) form. This operation is always performed when you run the process on the form. #Clears all transaction history details for the inventory account in the Inventory module, which you can view in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_70_00|Historical Inventory Valuation] ([~/?ScreenId=IN617000|IN617000]) report; the process then rebuilds the history again and recalculates the balance of the inventory account in the module by the released inventory transactions. To perform this operation, you have to select the '''Rebuild Item History''' check box on the form and specify the starting financial period. The system rebuilds the transaction history for each financial period starting from the specified one up to the last activity period in the module. [anchor|#_eb01d874-4c04-4665-88ba-0ae3880b102b] ==Reports and Forms Used for Reconciliation in the Inventory module== To review the ending balance of an inventory account for a historical period, you can use any of the following forms and reports:[anchor|#_efe4ed4b-b971-4fcd-b143-70b83fa3d929] *[HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_70_00|Historical Inventory Valuation] ([~/?ScreenId=IN617000|IN617000]) report in the summary format: The summary report shows transaction summaries by inventory item, grouped by the account and subaccount to which the summarized transactions have been processed in the Inventory module. For each item, the summaries by period are presented for each period within the specified range. The first row of the summary shows the cost of the item for the account, subaccount, and period; the second row shows the quantity of the item. The '''Account/Subaccount Beginning Balance''' and '''Account/Subaccount Ending Balance''' lines show the beginning and ending balances on the subaccount for the selected period range. If you do not use subaccounts, the '''Account/Subaccount Ending Balance''' line shows the ending balance of the inventory account. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_30_00|Inventory Transactions by Account] ([~/?ScreenId=IN403000|IN403000]) form: With the inventory account and period selected in the Summary area, the form shows inventory transactions processed to the selected inventory account and financial period. Each record is an inventory transaction that corresponds to a line in the released inventory entry. The '''Beginning Balance''' and '''Ending Balance''' columns show running totals calculated by the listed transactions. If you specify additional filtering parameters on the form, the running totals are recalculated. '''Beginning Balance''' in the first row starts from the beginning balance of the inventory account for the selected period. *:By default, the transaction lines are ordered by the transaction date (the '''Date''' column), then by the transaction type (the '''Tran. Type''' column), the reference number (the '''Reference Nbr.''' column), and the line number in the transaction. *:'''Fin. Period''' shows the financial period that is specified in the '''Post Period''' of the inventory transaction. '''Tran. Period''' shows the financial period to which the transaction date belongs, which is not necessarily equal to the post period. The corresponding General Ledger transaction is posted to the '''Post Period''' of the inventory transaction. *:The '''Period''' that you specify in the form settings filters transactions by the '''Post Period''' or '''Tran. Period''' of the transaction. If the '''By Financial Period''' check box is selected, the transactions are filtered by '''Post Period'''; otherwise, they are posted by '''Tran. Period'''. With the '''Start Date''' and '''End Date''' parameters on the form, you can also filter the transactions within the specified financial period. *:In the last row, the '''Ending Balance''' column shows the ending balance of the account for the selected period.
To review the ending balance of an inventory account for the last activity period, you can use one of the following forms and reports:[anchor|#_ba859469-49ae-4a58-898c-0d1ab23c48ee] *The [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_70_00|Historical Inventory Valuation] report in the summary format *The [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_30_00|Inventory Transactions by Account] form * The [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_55_00|Inventory Valuation] ([~/?ScreenId=IN615500|IN615500]) report in the summary format: The report shows the ending balance of the inventory account for the last activity period in the Inventory module.
To review the ending balance of an inventory account in the General Ledger module, you use the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\GL_63_20_00|Trial Balance Summary] ([~/?ScreenId=GL632000|GL632000]) report. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Financials\GL__CON_Chart_of_Accounts|Chart of Accounts] *[HelpRoot_Financials\Finance_ClosingPeriods_GeneralInfo|Closing Financial Periods: General Information] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Financial_Period_Closing_Inventory|Financial Period Closing in the Inventory Module] *[HelpRoot_Financials\Finance_Processing_Batch_GeneralInfo|GL Transactions: General Information]

In Acumatica ERP, you can configure automated replenishment for stock items at your organization&rsquo;s warehouses.((({S:Warn}The functionality that supports automated replenishment is available if the ''Inventory Replenishment'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. ))) If the ''Multiple Warehouses'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] form, you can assign different replenishment methods to different items of inventory stocked at different warehouses and enter warehouse-specific item settings (such as safety stock, reorder point, and maximum quantity) to be used as parameters for these methods. Different items may require diverse parameters because of varying customer demand for the items and different numbers of days required to receive the requested quantities from the vendors. If the ''Multiple Warehouses'' feature is disabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] form, you can assign replenishment classes to particular stock items.{br}
By using forecast models, you can fine-tune such parameters as safety stock, reorder point, and maximum quantities based on sales statistics. Thus, by using automated replenishment, your company can strike a balance between overstocks and stockouts.{br}
In this chapter, you will read about automated replenishment and availability calculation in Acumatica ERP. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#_27dfda01-84b5-432e-81ac-89d96d5f40e2] {| class="checklist invisiblechecklist" | width="100%" |- | [anchor|#ul_arn_lnl_3n] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Automated_Replenishment|Automated Replenishment] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Configuration_of_Automated_Replenishment|Configuration of Automated Replenishment] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Replenishment_Parameters|Replenishment Methods and Their Parameters] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Replenishment_Based_on_Demand_Forecast_Model|Replenishment Parameters Based on Demand Forecast ] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Example_Replenishment_Calculation|An Example of Replenishment Parameter Calculation]
